member.remarks:
Before using the API, you must create a class that implements  and expose it in the assembly.
First implement IPlugin, as in this example:

public class MyPlugin : IPlugin
{
     public void OnLoad()
     { 
         // Register handlers and app buttons here ..
     }
     
     public void OnUnload()
     {
        // Cleanup
     }
}

Then expose the implementation in the AssemblyInfo.cs:

// ..
[assembly: AssemblyExportPlugin(typeof(MyNamespace.MyPlugin))]
// ..

For example, after the user finishes the scan job, you can return back to the main page
like this:

// NOTE: Plugins should only use the NavigationService when they have control over the UI!
// Also, all NavigationService methods must occur in the UI thread.
NavigationService navService = UIManager.NavigationService;

// Go to the main page
navService.Navigate(StandardPages.CreateMainPage());

            Plugins can handle requests sent to their configuration pages.
            
            class MyHttpHandler : IHttpHandler
            {
                void Process(IHttpRequest request, IHttpResponse response, IHttpSession session)
                {
                    if (!request.IsAjax)
                    {
                        // Handle AJAX requests here ..
                    }
                    else
                    {
                        // Send "Hello World" response.
                        byte[] content = Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes("
Hello, World");
                        response.Encoding = Encoding.UTF8;
                        response.ContentLength = content.Length;
                        response.ContentType = "text/html";
                        response.SendHeaders();
                        response.SendBody(content);
                    }
                }
            }

Plugins that require configuration through the configuration server can use this class to register their own to handle requests going to a certain prefix. When the prefix is registered, a special button will appear on the main page of the server, allowing the IT admin to enter that prefix.
WebServer.RegisterHttpHandler("XYZ Document System", "/xyzdoc", new XYZConfigHttpHandler());
Upon browsing to the server's root, e.g. http://[server IP]/, the IT admin will be able to see a link/button on the UI, "XYZ Document System" that they can click to browse to http://[server IP]/xyzdoc.

